              "id": "shared2011_s2_text_prompt_1",
              "role": "PROMPT",
              "type": "paragraph",
              "value": "Scientists announced tonight that they have “buckets” of water on the Moon following the analysis of data from a spacecraft that was deliberately crashed into a lunar crater last month."
            },
            {
              "id": "shared2011_s2_text_prompt_2",
              "role": "PROMPT",
              "type": "paragraph",
              "value": "The researchers said the evidence for the existence of significant bodies of water ice hidden in polar craters on the Moon is “definitive” and that the total quantities could be big enough to support a permanently-manned lunar base."
            },
            {
              "id": "shared2011_s2_text_prompt_3",
              "role": "PROMPT",
              "type": "paragraph",
              "value": "It is the first time that the US National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) have been so categorical about the discovery of water on the Moon. Previous studies had only suggested that the presence of water might be possible and then only in trace amounts."
            },
            {
              "id": "shared2011_s2_text_prompt_4",
              "role": "PROMPT",
              "type": "paragraph",
              "value": "One of the unsolved questions is how the water could have got to the Moon. One theory is that it arrived on a comet and never evaporated in the shaded polar craters where temperature is minus 220C."
            },
            {
              "id": "shared2011_s2_text_prompt_5",
              "role": "PROMPT",
              "type": "paragraph",
              "value": "NASA estimates that there are 12,500 square kilometers of permanently-shadowed terrain on the Moon and if the top one meter of this area were to hold just 1% by mass of water, this would still produce thousands of liters of water."
            }
          ]
        },
